members.extended:
Scalars become shape `(1, 1, 1)`, 1-D tensors become `(1, N, 1)`,
2-D tensors gain a trailing unit axis to become `(M, N, 1)`;
tensors with rank $\geq 3$ pass through unchanged.

notes:
Mathematical definition:



$$
\text{fmax}(a_i, b_i) =
\begin{cases}
    b_i,           & a_i = \text{NaN}, \\
    a_i,           & b_i = \text{NaN}, \\
    \max(a_i, b_i),& \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$

Contrast with `lucid.maximum`, which propagates NaN per IEEE 754.

Mathematical definition:



$$
\text{fmin}(a_i, b_i) =
\begin{cases}
    b_i,           & a_i = \text{NaN}, \\
    a_i,           & b_i = \text{NaN}, \\
    \min(a_i, b_i),& \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$

Contrast with `lucid.minimum`, which propagates NaN per IEEE 754.

members.extended:
Composite over Python `itertools` — non-differentiable (treats
the values as opaque scalars).  Use only for low-rate utility code;
don't put on a hot path.

parameters.description:
When `True` add to existing values (duplicate indices sum);
when `False` (default) overwrite (duplicate indices resolve
to the last write).
